Time dependent Cox: sensitivity analysis in patients who survived over 180 days

J.S. González-Martínez

2021-09-03

Below are the results for the second series of Cox proportional hazard analyses. The analyses below treat covariates as time-dependent and focus on patients who survived more than 180 days. We developed univariate and multivariate models.

Further data processing: Calculate time intervals required for analyses 
#verify no observations have a time of observation greater than overall time of survival 
nrow(filter(all_df, time_survob > time_surv))
## [1] 0
#reorder df so time intervals are ordered by ID and time_survob is ordered in descending order within ID clusters

all_df <- all_df[with(all_df, order(brc_id, -time_survob)),]

#calculate time 1

all_df <- all_df %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(time1 = time_surv - time_survob) 

#reorder df so time intervals are ordered by ID and time1 is ordered in asceding order within ID clusters

all_df <- all_df[with(all_df, order(brc_id, time1)),]

#calculate time2

all_df <- all_df %>% 
  group_by(brc_id) %>% 
  mutate(time2 = lead(time1, default = 0))

freq_per_info <- function(var) {#function to generate a table with frequencies and percentages
  library(epiDisplay) #library required 
  tab1(var, 
       sort.group = "decreasing",
       cum.percentage = T,
       graph = F)}

Analysis
Establish death event rules

Censor data based on time intervals

Rules:

  1. Check the last time interval per patient (i.e., when time_surv = time 2)

  2. If there is a date of death recorded for that patient, and that date of death was before the cohort’s end span (“2019-05-01”), then the interval corresponds to a death within the study period

  3. All other observations shall be censored

all_df <- all_df %>% 
   dplyr::mutate(event_death = ifelse((time_surv == time2) & !is.na(Date_Of_Death) & 
                                      (Date_Of_Death  <= "2019-05-01"), 1, 0)) %>% 
   dplyr::mutate(event_death = as.numeric(event_death))

table(all_df$event_death)
## 
##     0     1 
## 44890  3062
Univariate models

Functionalise graph plotting

#function to customise plot of Schoenfeld's test results

plot_schoenfeld <- function(resx, var_name) {
  my_plot0 <- ggcoxzph(resx, 
                       title = print(paste("Schoenfeld's test results for", var_name)),
                       xlab = "Time (days)", 
                       ylab = print(paste("Beta(t) for", var_name)))
    
  return(my_plot0)}

#function to customise plots of survival curves (only works for continuous variables)

plot_surv <- function(fitobj, var_name, namesobj) { 
 my_plot1 <- ggsurvplot(fitobj, #default
           palette = "nejm", #default
           censor.size = 2, #default
           title = print("Survival probablity in OxNHS dementia patients: Survivors 180+ days"),
          font.title = c(14),
           subtitle = print(paste("Adjusted for", var_name, "(time-dependent analysis)")),
           font.subtitle = c(14, "italic"),
           xlab = "Time (days)", #default
           legend.title = str_to_title(var_name),
           legend.labs = namesobj)
    
  return(my_plot1)}
